This paper deals with wireless networks and game theory, which are both relevant to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) category. The use of game theory to model the behavior of stations and relays suggests that the paper could also belong to the Game Theory (cs.GT) category. The focus on preventing selfish behavior and preserving appropriate QoS suggests that the paper could also belong to the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) category. The use of reputation-based incentives suggests that the paper could also belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) category. Finally, the use of a trusted third party to limit selfish behavior suggests that the paper could also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) category.
